      {
        "type": "Personal Nimshal",
        "content": "Any time we work to improve, this is Avodah. We work on improving the quantity and quality of our good midos, Torah study, davening, and mitzvos.\nSpecifically, there are two stages in Avodah:\nThe first step is like a farmer working on his field—he uses the dirt to grow food, but the earth remains earth. So too, at first we cultivate and reveal the hidden potential of our neshamah (our nefesh elokis); yet, our body (and nefesh habehamis) remains the same and desires physical things. For example, at first we develop good manners (derech eretz) so that we don’t act like an animal. Then, we use our bodies and talents to serve Hashem through Torah and mitzvos. When we are involved in holy things, our Neshamah shines and we are inspired, but later when we go back to our physical life, we still desire the same physical pleasures.\nThe second step is like a tanner, who transforms raw hides into beautiful leathers. So too, we transform the nature of our body (and our nefesh habehamis and yetzer hara). When we work very hard to serve Hashem, and have self-sacrifice (mesiras nefesh) for Torah and mitzvos—especially for helping others (tzedakah and ahavas yisrael)—this transforms our nature, so that even our body and animal soul want to serve Hashem."
      },
